## Server vs client components
- **Default:** Server Component (no `'use client'`).
- **Use `'use client'`** only when you need React state, effects, browser APIs, or Echo.
- **Data fetching:** Prefer server actions and server-side fetches. Client-side fetches only for live data via Echo.

## Component pattern

```tsx
// app/(app)/locations/[id]/page.tsx — Server Component
import { LocationCard } from '@/components/locations/location-card';
import { fetchLocationState } from '@/lib/api';

export default async function LocationDetailPage({
  params,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>;
}) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const initialState = await fetchLocationState(Number(id));

  return <LocationCard initialState={initialState} />;
}
```

```tsx
// components/locations/location-card.tsx — Client Component for live updates
'use client';

import { useLocationState } from '@/hooks/use-location-state';
import type { LocationState } from '@/types/api';

interface LocationCardProps {
  initialState: LocationState;
}

export function LocationCard({ initialState }: LocationCardProps) {
  const state = useLocationState(initialState.location_id, initialState);

  return (
    <div className="rounded-2xl border bg-card p-6 shadow-sm">
      <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-maroon-700">{state.location_name}</h2>
      <p className="mt-2 text-5xl font-bold">{state.tokens_remaining.toLocaleString()}</p>
      <p className="text-sm text-muted-foreground">tokens remaining</p>
      {/* ... */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Hook pattern (WebSocket subscription)

```tsx
// hooks/use-location-state.ts
'use client';

import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { getEcho } from '@/lib/echo';
import type { LocationState } from '@/types/api';

export function useLocationState(
  locationId: number,
  initial: LocationState,
): LocationState {
  const [state, setState] = useState<LocationState>(initial);

  useEffect(() => {
    const echo = getEcho();
    const channel = echo.private(`location.${locationId}`);

    channel.listen('.LocationStateUpdated', (e: LocationState) => setState(e));

    return () => {
      echo.leave(`location.${locationId}`);
    };
  }, [locationId]);

  return state;
}
```

## API client pattern

```ts
// lib/api.ts
import type { ApiResponse, LocationState } from '@/types/api';

const BASE = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL!;

export async function fetchLocationState(locationId: number): Promise<LocationState> {
  const res = await fetch(`${BASE}/api/v1/locations/${locationId}/state`, {
    credentials: 'include',
    headers: { Accept: 'application/json' },
    next: { revalidate: 0 }, // always fresh
  });

  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`fetchLocationState failed: ${res.status}`);

  const json = (await res.json()) as ApiResponse<LocationState>;
  if (!json.success) throw new Error(json.error?.message ?? 'API error');
  return json.data;
}
```

## Styling

- **Tailwind first.** No CSS modules unless absolutely needed.
- **Palette:** maroon-700 (#6D1A2C), gold-400 (#D4A437) for brand. Use Tailwind config tokens, not raw hex.
- **shadcn/ui** for primitives. Don't write your own Button, Dialog, Tabs.
- **Mobile-responsive.** Operators may use phones in the field.

## State conventions

- Use server state via fetch + Echo subscription, not Redux/Zustand.
- Local UI state via `useState`. No Context unless cross-cutting (auth, Echo).
- Forms: `react-hook-form` + `zod` for validation.

## What NOT to do

- ❌ Don't use `console.log` in committed code
- ❌ Don't fetch without typing the response
- ❌ Don't use `'use client'` unless needed
- ❌ Don't write inline styles
- ❌ Don't add a new dependency without justification
- ❌ Don't bypass Echo for live state (no polling)
